<Base title="What Is Neuroplastic Pain?">
  <article class="container page-section">
    <h1>What Is Neuroplastic Pain?</h1>

    <p>
      <strong>Neuroplastic pain</strong> is chronic pain caused by changes in your nervous system — not by ongoing 
      tissue damage. Your brain has learned a pain pattern and keeps producing pain signals even after 
      the original injury has healed.
    </p>

    <div class="card" style="margin: 1.5rem 0;">
      <p style="margin: 0; font-weight: 600;">Quick definition:</p>
      <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0;">Pain generated by hypersensitive neural pathways in the brain and spinal cord, not by structural damage in the body.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>How does it work?</h2>
    <p>
      Normally, pain is a warning signal. You touch something hot — your nerves send a signal to your brain — 
      it hurts — you pull away. The pain stops when the danger passes.
    </p>
    <p>
      With neuroplastic pain, the danger is gone but the alarm system stays stuck on high. This is called 
      <strong>central sensitization</strong>. Your nervous system becomes so sensitive that normal sensations — 
      sitting, bending, light touch — get interpreted as pain.
    </p>

    <h2>Is the pain real?</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Yes, 100% real.</strong> Brain scans (fMRI) show the same pain-processing regions lighting up 
      as with a fresh injury. The pain is not "in your head" — it's in your nervous system. The difference 
      is not in what you feel, but in what causes it.
    </p>

    <h2>What conditions involve neuroplastic pain?</h2>
    <p>Research supports neuroplastic mechanisms in:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Fibromyalgia</li>
      <li>Chronic back pain</li>
      <li>Chronic migraines and tension headaches</li>
      <li>Irritable bowel syndrome (IBS)</li>
      <li>Temporomandibular joint disorder (TMJ)</li>
      <li>Chronic pelvic pain</li>
      <li>Chronic fatigue syndrome (ME/CFS)</li>
      <li>Long COVID pain syndromes</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      These conditions often overlap — having one increases the likelihood of others — which is 
      exactly what you'd expect if they share a common mechanism: central sensitization.
    </p>

    <h2>How do you know if you have it?</h2>
    <p>Key indicators include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Pain that persists after injuries have healed</li>
      <li>Pain that moves or spreads to different body parts</li>
      <li>Sensitivity to light, sound, touch, or smell</li>
      <li>Pain triggered by things that shouldn't hurt (allodynia)</li>
      <li>Stress and emotions make pain significantly worse</li>
      <li>Treatments targeting the body (surgery, injections, physical therapy) haven't worked</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Can it be treated?</h2>
    <p>
      Yes. This is the hopeful part. If your brain can learn pain, it can also learn to unlearn it. 
      Brain-based approaches like <strong>Pain Reprocessing Therapy (PRT)</strong> and 
      <strong>Emotional Awareness and Expression Therapy (EAET)</strong> directly target the neural 
      pathways generating pain. A landmark 2022 trial found 66% of chronic back pain patients became 
      pain-free after 4 weeks of PRT.
    </p>

